00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.790
So we're here to talk about
spies and intelligence

00:01:37.790 --> 00:01:39.820
and maybe hacking, who knows?

00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:44.060
But it is quite an honor to
introduce this morning's panel.

00:01:44.060 --> 00:01:47.710
Our moderator is Kai Bird,
the author of "The Good Spy:

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:49.510
The Life and Death
of Robert Ames."

00:01:49.510 --> 00:01:52.860
He's also the co-author
of the Pulitzer-winning

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:56.040
"American Prometheus" on the
life of Robert Oppenheimer,

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:57.880
which I must confesses is one

00:01:57.880 --> 00:01:59.610
of the greatest biographies
I've ever read.

00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:02.190
No surprise, Kai is also
director of the Leon Levy Center

00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:05.190
for Biography at the City
University of New York.

00:02:05.190 --> 00:02:08.460
Our panelists are
Washington Post columnist

00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:11.380
and novelist David
Ignatius, author of 10 novels,

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:15.040
most recently "Quantum Spy,"
spy novelist Joseph Kanon,

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:20.160
author most recently of
"Defectors," and Adam Sisman,

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:24.810
whose latest book is a
biography and he has explained

00:02:24.810 --> 00:02:26.590
to me the proper
way to pronounce it.

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:29.550
It is not le Carre it's
le Carre [pronouncing].

00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:31.760
We can have a debate
about this later.

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:34.070
In addition to being
part of the panel,

00:02:34.070 --> 00:02:37.660
they'll be signing
